  <para>
    <classname>DisplayMethods</classname> are the techniques used to
    draw the &oof2; objects, such as <link
    linkend='Section-Concepts-Microstructure-Image'>Images</link> and <link
    linkend='Section-Concepts-Skeleton'>Skeletons</link>, in the <link
    linkend='Chapter-Graphics'>Graphics Window</link>.  Each <link
    linkend='Section-Graphics-Layer'>Layer</link> in the Graphics
    Window corresponds to a single <classname>DisplayMethod</classname>.
  </para>

  <para>
    <classname>DisplayMethods</classname> may take parameters, which
    are described in the sections for each specific method. These
    parameters govern things like line widths, colors,
    <foreignphrase>etc</foreignphrase>.  One thing that the parameters
    do <emphasis>not</emphasis> govern is the object (&image;, &mesh;,
    <foreignphrase>etc.</foreignphrase>) which the
    <classname>DisplayMethod</classname> displays.  That is determined
    by the <link linkend='Section-Graphics-Layer'>Layer</link>
    containing the <classname>DisplayMethod</classname>.  This
    arrangement allows an object to be displayed by more than one
    <classname>DisplayMethod</classname> simultaneously.
  </para>
  <para>
    <classname>DisplayMethods</classname> are added to <link
    linkend="Section-Graphics-Layer"><classname>Layers</classname></link>
    and assembled into <link
    linkend="Section-Graphics-LayerSet"><classname>LayerSets</classname></link>
    by the <xref linkend="MenuItem-OOF.LayerEditor.LayerSet"/> menu
    and the <link linkend="Section-Graphics-LayerEditor">Layer
    Editor</link> window.
  </para>


